version: "1.0.0"
title: Execute GitHub Issue
description: |
  Read a GitHub issue conforming to the claude_and_goose issue format
  (see prompts/issue-format.md), execute its subtask checklist,
  comment with results, and open a PR if files were changed.

parameters:
  - key: issue_number
    input_type: string
    requirement: required
    description: GitHub issue number to execute (e.g. "1")
  - key: repo
    input_type: string
    requirement: optional
    default: why-pengo/claude_and_goose
    description: owner/repo to run against

extensions:
  - type: builtin
    name: developer
    timeout: 600
  - type: stdio
    name: github
    cmd: github-mcp-server
    args:
      - stdio
    envs:
      GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN: ${GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN}
    timeout: 300

prompt: |
  You are executing GitHub issue #{{ issue_number }} in {{ repo }}.
  The full operating rules are in `prompts/goose-system.md` — read
  that file first if you haven't already this session.

  # Step 1 — Read the issue
  Use the github extension to fetch issue #{{ issue_number }} from
  {{ repo }}. Read the full body. Then read every file path and
  follow every link listed in its Context section.

  If the issue is missing any required section (Goal, Context,
  Subtasks, Acceptance criteria, Out of scope), STOP and post a
  comment asking for the missing pieces. Do not guess scope.

  # Step 2 — Branch
  Create branch `goose/issue-{{ issue_number }}-<slug>` from the
  latest `main`. The slug is 3–5 kebab-case words drawn from the
  issue title.

  # Step 3 — Execute subtasks in order
  For each checklist item:
    - Make the single concrete change it describes.
    - Verify it (run the test, build, or command listed).
    - Commit with a conventional-commit message
      (`feat:`, `fix:`, `test:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`).
  Stop and comment on the issue if a subtask is ambiguous. Do not
  invent scope. If a subtask fails twice, stop and report — do not
  loop.

  # Step 4 — Verify acceptance criteria
  Run every observable check listed under Acceptance criteria. If any
  fail, fix and re-verify before opening the PR.

  # Step 5 — Open the PR (only if files changed)
  Title: match the issue title.
  Body must include, in this order:
    - `Closes #{{ issue_number }}`
    - `## Summary` — what changed, 2–4 bullets
    - `## Verification` — each acceptance criterion and how you
      confirmed it
    - `## Subtasks` — mirror of the issue checklist, all checked
    - `## Follow-ups` (optional) — anything out of scope you noticed

  # Step 6 — Comment on the issue
  Post a comment on #{{ issue_number }} with:
    - Status: ✅ done | ⚠️ partial | ❌ blocked
    - Link to the PR (or to the branch if nothing changed)
    - Anything surprising

  # Rules
  - Never close the issue directly — `Closes` on the PR does that on merge.
  - Never force-push. Never skip hooks (no `--no-verify`).
  - Never edit `main` directly.
  - One issue, one PR. Out-of-scope work goes under Follow-ups, not
    into this PR.
---
# Goose configuration for claude_and_goose
#
# Load this in addition to the user's standard config by exporting:
#   export GOOSE_ADDITIONAL_CONFIG_FILES="$(pwd)/goose.yaml"
# Or copy/symlink it to ~/.config/goose/config.yaml if this is the
# only Goose project you run.
#
# Verify with:  goose info -v   (should show GOOSE_PROVIDER, model,
# and the github extension)
#
# Required env at runtime:
#   GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN — for the github MCP extension

GOOSE_PROVIDER: ollama
GOOSE_MODEL: qwen3.6:latest
OLLAMA_HOST: http://bazzite.local:11434

# Bump these if Goose cuts off on long reasoning steps. qwen3.6 has a
# generous context window and the 5090 has VRAM to spare.
GOOSE_CONTEXT_LIMIT: 65536
GOOSE_MAX_TURNS: 100

extensions:
  developer:
    type: builtin
    name: developer
    enabled: true
    timeout: 600

  # Official GitHub MCP server — Go binary from github/github-mcp-server.
  # Install once with: brew install github-mcp-server
  github:
    type: stdio
    name: github
    cmd: github-mcp-server
    args:
      - stdio
    envs:
      GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN: ${GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN}
    enabled: true
    timeout: 300
---
# claude_and_goose

An evaluation harness for a two-agent code workflow:

- **Claude Code** is the planner. It reads context, decomposes work,
  and files structured GitHub Issues.
- **Goose** is the executor. It reads one issue at a time, executes
  its subtasks, comments with results, and opens a PR.

This repo holds the recipes, prompts, and eval results. It is *not*
the target project — it is the rig.

## Pieces

| Path                          | Purpose |
|-------------------------------|---------|
| `CLAUDE.md`                   | What Claude Code reads on every session |
| `goose.yaml`                  | Provider + extension config (Ollama on `bazzite.local`, `qwen3.6:latest`) |
| `recipes/execute-issue.yaml`  | Core recipe: read issue → execute subtasks → PR |
| `recipes/plan-epic.yaml`      | Stub for future Goose-driven issue authoring |
| `prompts/goose-system.md`     | System prompt Goose runs with |
| `prompts/issue-format.md`     | Canonical issue template |
| `evals/`                      | One folder per eval run |
| `scripts/new-eval.sh`         | Scaffold a new `evals/eval-NN/` directory |

## Execution environment

Ollama host (`bazzite.local`):

- AMD Ryzen 9 9900X (12C/24T)
- 96 GB DDR5
- NVIDIA RTX 5090, 32 GB VRAM
- Running `qwen3.6:latest` (36B params, Q4_K_M, ~24 GB)

## Running an eval

1. A `goose-task` issue exists, is `ready-for-execution`, and has no
   open dependencies.
2. Install Goose (see https://goose-docs.ai). Not installed by this
   repo.
3. Point Goose at this config and verify:
   ```
   export GOOSE_ADDITIONAL_CONFIG_FILES="$(pwd)/goose.yaml"
   export GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN=...   # for the github MCP extension
   goose info -v                              # confirm provider/model/extensions resolved
   ```
4. Scaffold an eval directory and run the recipe:
   ```
   ./scripts/new-eval.sh 01
   goose run --recipe recipes/execute-issue.yaml \
     --params issue_number=1 \
     | tee evals/eval-01/goose-session.log
   ```
5. Write `evals/eval-01/result.md` (template scaffolded by the script).

